In the shadow of extinction: Three cheetah cubs born in Iran
The world's fastest animal is falling victim to brutal hunting, droughts and deadly road accidents across the Islamic Republic •
As a result, their number dropped to less than 20 cheetahs.
Three Asian cheetah cubs recently emerged into the world's air in the Islamic Republic of Iran.
It is a rare birth, which only slightly improves the tragic condition of the animal which is endangered in the country following droughts, hunts and fatal road accidents.
This is the first birth of a cheetah in captivity in Iran.
It should be noted that the Islamic Republic is one of the last countries in the world where cheetahs still live in the wild.
The Iranian news agency IRNA reported that the veterinary team in charge of the Turan National Park in the northern province of Semnan decided on a caesarean birth in captivity.
It was also noted that less than 20 cheetahs have been documented in seven different districts of the state in recent times.
In the wake of the danger of their extinction, the United Nations executed a protection plan for them back in 2001.
Now, in Iran, it is hoped the new cubs could bring about an increase in the cheetah population in the future.
Last January, Iran's Deputy Minister of Environmental Affairs Hassan Akbari said that the country's cheetah population had dramatically shrunk from 100 cheetahs in 2010 to just 12 cheetahs.
"Their situation is extremely serious," Akbari said, noting that the cheetahs have fallen victim to drought in their living areas, hunting and even road accidents.
The cheetah is considered the fastest animal in the world, capable of reaching a speed of about 100 km / h.
Cheetahs can be found in various places around the globe, from India to Senegal in West Africa.
Spotify wants to upgrade your car: We tested the Car Thing
Quietly, Spotify began to try its luck in the world of hardware as well •
After years of development - Car Thing was unveiled and launched as a small experiment in the US •
We got our hands on the first device in Israel •
Make your old cars smart.
The Car Thing is Spotify's first hardware product, and was built specifically to provide a solution for people with older vehicles.
A few weeks ago, I got an initial opportunity to try the new product, which is currently only available to individual experimenters in the US, here in Israel.
For me, the timing of the shipment was outstanding, as our home vehicle broke down and we had to drive for several days with a replacement vehicle with an old system.
After two weeks of toying around, I realized how the car thing could easily become an integral part of many people's system.
On the other hand, with a long waiting list and uncertainty regarding a global launch, I believe that many will prefer to use other solutions already.
From idea to reality
Sometime in 2018, Spotify users started receiving an interesting offer in their email inbox - the option to purchase a new device with voice control and fourth-generation connectivity, which would turn any old car system into a smart one.
The rumors slowly faded until a year later, when the Financial Times website revealed that the company was planning to soon introduce a new car product that simulates a smart radio with Bluetooth connections.
A few months later, these rumors returned to the headlines again after the music service was updated with the vehicle mode - the same one we now know from the app - which is activated as soon as the smartphone detects a connection to the system in the car.
Two years have passed since then.
After countless rumors and leaks, Spotify unveiled "Car Thing," its smart system for vehicles, last April.
Spotify has chosen to release the new device in a very limited way, with a long waiting list and many delays when it comes to shipments.
So of course, right after the press conference she held, I went on the website and signed up.
Two months later, the long-awaited announcement arrived.
Reconnecting to the site will give me the opportunity to purchase the device with a small surprise - it will not cost me anything.
After another month of waiting, the courier finally knocked on my door, accompanied by a small box with the Spotify logo on it.
The car thing thing
First and foremost, Spotify's device impressed me greatly with its build quality.
And a little smaller than my iPhone 11 and features a large, bright and sharp touch screen on the front than I expected.
Also, you'll find alongside the screen a round button and dial that you can rotate to navigate between the interface screens.
And despite the huge dial, which you can see in the photos, the Car Thing manages to maintain a relatively thin profile and not protrude too much from the dashboard.
Personally, I would have preferred the company to allow changing the activity of the dial in order for me to control the volume of the smartphone, as I can also navigate using the touchscreen.
Perhaps this will be possible in a future version update.
The device comes in a small, minimalist cardboard box, which includes, among other things, a USB Type C cable and various adapters for installing it.
Many of you probably remember how in the past we used to disconnect the radios and hide them in a drawer after getting out of the car.
The Car Thing certainly brings that feeling back with its form.
All the adapters were attached to the body of the device using a magnet that was very strong, which prevented it from falling even when driving on dirt roads.
In addition, throughout the top you can find small buttons, which can be easily set to play various playlists or podcasts.
By long-pressing one of the buttons while listening, or by a request from the voice assistant, I set up some playlists that I hear frequently and the radio show that I listen to every morning on the go.
In doing so, the feature made me feel like the Car Thing is more like a car radio than an extension of my smartphone.
From an old car to a smart car
After a fairly simple physical setup, I connected the Car Thing to the mains.
I was pleasantly surprised by the setup process.
The instructions were clear, connecting to the Spotify app took less than 5 minutes, and a few moments later I reached the home screen.
In fact, the device connects to the smartphone through Bluetooth and controls the app like a remote, so it can copy all our account information from it.
That means you'll still need to connect your smartphone to the car, either via Bluetooth or an AUX cable, to hear the music.
The home screen is familiar to all users of the app, as like the application on a smartphone, it puts an emphasis on the album images and playlists.
Also, on the home screen, like the one in the app, you can find music recommendations according to your taste, the search screen and your personal library.
As mentioned, you can navigate between the different screens using the touchscreen or using the manual dial.
Moreover, you can at any given moment call the device's voice assistant by saying "Hey Spotify."
With it, you can play songs, playlists, albums, and even search for podcasts.
From Sony, she recognized my voice quite easily even when the music was playing in the background and the air conditioner was blowing directly on the device.
This is probably due to the four microphones installed at the top.
It is important to note that at the moment the voice assistant does not support Hebrew, and as of the time of publication of the article, there is no information about when such an update will arrive.
So is it worth waiting for him?
My experience of using the device was great, which is a positive surprise to me given that it's still in an initial release phase.
Even with intensive use on long journeys, the device continued to work smoothly without disconnecting from my smartphone.
Still, from time to time there is a small stutter in the interface, but I believe that Spotify will address such bugs with future version updates.
It is evident that the Swedish company has worked on it a lot in recent years, and among the various versions that have leaked on the Internet during this period, the design of the final product is probably my favorite.
Still, when I saw the Car Thing for the first time, I wondered who exactly the company was trying to designate it for.
After all, his activity boils down to controlling the app on the smartphone, and not much beyond that.
How is it different from buying a car stand for a few shekels and connecting it so that the smartphone is closer to us when driving?
That question is reinforced when considering that iPhones and Android devices are much more powerful than Spotify's, and most times will buy the user a lot more functionality.
Despite all this, as I used Car Thing more and more, I realized how it could improve the driving experience.
Being able to see the Waze on my smartphone screen and control the music on a completely different screen, is one I've learned to appreciate over the past two weeks.
One question remains - will Spotify even launch the device to the general public?
And if so, will it be launched here in our small country as well?
The Swedish company is not telling much at the moment.
It hasn't even shared how many experimenters for the device it's currently running around the world, and how many it plans to add in the limited launch in the United States.
The only thing we know for sure is that the price is expected to be $79.
In the meantime, the Car Thing provides an initial glimpse of a concept that Spotify has been trying to crack for years.
Spotify Israel said that there is currently no information about a plan to launch the device in Israel.
