Did you recruit talent for the company?
Make sure your competitors don't "steal" it from you.
The economy is still in a labor market that is largely dominated by workers, and this is doubly true when it comes to the most desirable workers - the talents.
Here are some tips to help you keep it safe in the workplace
.
Despite the increase recorded in the last month, the unemployment rate in Israel continues to be among the lowest in the world, and in the top ten among the OECD countries, with a rate of 3.5% (150.6 thousand unemployed, according to the Central Bureau of Statistics).
In other words, the economy is still in a labor market that is largely dominated by workers, and this is doubly true when it comes to the most desirable workers - the talents.
As for those professionals and managers who are centers of proven knowledge, experience and ability - the trends in the labor market show that competition for them, the talents as they are called by employers, still exists in full force.
What this means for employers is that in the current state of the labor market, they do not have the luxury of resting on their laurels even a minute after the recruitment of a coveted talent, since as soon as he enters the company's gates - another company will already try to kidnap him.
In other words, the competition for talent is so fierce that many, even after they are recruited, will continue to receive a variety of tempting job offers, with 30% of employees actually leaving only a month after receiving the job and starting work.
This is why smart employers will immediately move from the stage of recruiting talent to the stage of retaining it, when the path begins first and foremost with preparation in advance and taking creativity already in the process of absorbing it.
An efficient, structured and thoughtful absorption process will make the talent excited about his new workplace from the very first day and even look forward to the future.
Here are some tips on how to prepare and manage a proper absorption process that will help preserve the new talent:
It's not a secret - sharing and organization readiness <unk>
Share the factors that will work with him on his recruitment, explain to them why he is vital and important to the company and the role, and how you see his contribution.
A new employee who arrives at a place where he is expected and understands his value, will feel welcome and strive to prove the expectations placed on him.
Knowledge is power - coordinating expectations
Already on the first day, they held a conversation with the talent to coordinate expectations.
Get to know his professional background and see where he sees himself in the future, so you can introduce him to the diverse and unique tools you and the workplace can provide him to get there.
We are all people - personal acquaintance
During the days of absorption, try to get to know the talent beyond his professional qualities and take an interest in his hobbies and interests.
A new employee who shows interest in him and allows him to realize and express himself beyond the limits of his job will appreciate this and want to keep it.
Curiosity is promoted <unk>
Already at the absorption stage, you can create an attractiveness that will make the talent want to integrate quickly.
Do this not necessarily by talking about bonuses and benefits, but by exposing him to an exciting field or an interesting technology, since such stimuli to creativity lead to curiosity and growing interest in the workplace.
Also, encourage the talent to voice his thoughts and opinions on the various projects in the company and make it clear to him that they are important to the organization.
The author is the CEO of Manpower Israel - the largest placement and manpower company in Israel.
Electrification in your pocket: The cost of not closing coal-fired power plants in June - NIS 1 billion
A report by the Knesset Research and Information Center: The failure to close the coal plants on the date set in June 2022 is estimated at NIS 1 billion
• The Electric Company: "The fuel use policy is dictated first and foremost by the Ministry of Energy"
.
The economic cost of not closing the coal plants on the date set in June 2022 is estimated at NIS 1 billion for 2022, according to a report by the Knesset Research and Information Center.
According to the report, this cost is embodied in the consumer electricity tariff, which is expected to increase in the coming months due to the rise in the cost of coal.
In addition, in 2023, an additional excess amount of coal use of about 900,000 tons is expected, so this will be reflected in an additional cost to the electricity economy for not closing the coal plants, assuming that the price of natural gas will remain significantly lower relative to the price of coal.
The report states that the reduction of about NIS 1 billion in the electricity tariff in 2022 meant a reduction of about 4% in the electricity consumption tariff for the home consumer.
In other words, the economic cost of not closing the stations is about NIS 1 billion, and the total discount that could have been given to the home consumer is about 4%.
It should be noted that as part of the reform of the electricity sector, it was decided, among other things, to establish a subsidiary of the Electric Company, which will build units powered by natural gas, designed to replace the 4-1 coal-fired units at the Orot Rabin site.
Following this decision, a government decision was adopted in July 2018, which states that the operation of the 4-1 coal-fired production units at the Orot Rabin power plant must be stopped.
The decision set timetables, so that the construction of the first natural gas unit will begin in January 2020 and its operation will begin in June 2022, and accordingly, the coal-fired production units 4-1 will also cease to operate on this date.
The electricity company said in response: "The fuel use policy is dictated first and foremost by the Ministry of Energy.
In accordance with the ministry's decisions, a policy of reducing the use of coal to the minimum possible has been implemented in Israel for several years, even when the price of coal is lower than the price of gas. "
Paying the price: Everything you need to know ahead of the interest rate rise
Decrees constantly: Next week the interest rate on the shekel is expected to rise by half a percent •
How much will the payment on the mortgage cost?
And what is recommended to do? •
All the answers
The worsening inflation in Israel, which has already reached a rate of more than 4% over the past year, will force the Bank of Israel to raise the interest rate on the shekel as early as next week.
Analysts' estimates speak of a rate of increase ranging from 0.25% to 0.5%.
If the interest rate does rise by half a percentage point, it will already be 1.25%, the highest level in nine years.
This is after years of interest rates being close to zero.
The sharp increase in the interest rate makes mortgage repayments hundreds of shekels more expensive and weighs drastically on households.
With the help of Shai Bundle, a mortgage expert, we looked at how much more we will pay and what is recommended to do right now.
If the interest rate rises by half a percent - how much will the monthly payment on the mortgage cost?
On a mortgage of NIS 1.2 million, which consists of a 40% prime interest rate track, the monthly repayment will increase by NIS 125.
How much has the average mortgage gone up by since the beginning of the year?
Since the beginning of the year, this is a significantly sharper increase.
This is because interest rates in the other tracks that make up mortgages (and not just in the prime track) have also risen - in the index-linked track and in the fixed interest rate track.
If the interest rate does rise by half a percent, the increase in price will amount, according to Zror's estimate, to about NIS 620 on a mortgage of about NIS 1.2 million.
The prime route (40% in this route) will complete an increase of about NIS 280, assuming that there will be an increase of another 0.5% next month.
The index-linked variable interest rate track (26.7% in this track) will complete a rise in price of about NIS 120.
The fixed interest rate track - not indexed (33.3% in this track) will become more expensive by NIS 220.
So what is recommended to do today?
For those who have a mortgage that is mostly indexed, Bundle recommends considering recycling to non-indexed routes.
For mortgage holders whose monthly repayments have increased significantly and it is difficult for them to meet repayments - he recommends looking into recycling a mortgage and redeploying it for a longer period.
This is to reduce payments despite the increase in interest rates, as it is always better to meet repayments and not be insolvent.
Regarding new mortgage takers - he strongly recommends getting to know the different routes and adjusting the mortgage to their financial capabilities.
The same applies in the future when interest rates fall they will be able to do mortgage recycling with minimal early repayment fees.
Regarding apartment buyers from a contractor - Bundle recommends making payments to the contractor ahead of time and taking out a mortgage now.
It should be taken into account that the "construction input index" raises the price of the property significantly even after the purchase contract is signed.
The residential construction input price index increased by 6.6% over the past year.
Against the background of the increase in the cost of this measure, the Banking Supervision Department announced yesterday that it is considering mandating the creation of a mechanism that will allow the linkage to be included in the mortgages, but the final decision on the issue has not yet been made.
The price of gas is rising - and Israelis will have to pay more than 8 shekels per liter in July
The Ministry of Energy announced that the new price for a liter of 95-octane gasoline will be NIS 8.08.
At the same time, the reduction of half a shekel per liter in the tax on diesel will be extended until the end of 2022
A record of a decade: The price of gasoline will jump by 36 cents per liter - and will stand from July 1 at more than 8 shekels per liter.
The new price for a liter of 95-octane gasoline will be -8.08 and those who wish to enjoy full service will be required to pay another 21 cents per liter.
At the same time, the reduction of half a shekel per liter in the diesel tax will be extended until the end of 2022 - the tax authority said.
As mentioned, the price increase is due to the continued rise in oil prices, against the backdrop of the war between Russia and Ukraine and the rise in the dollar rate.
Had it not been for the half-shekel discount that the government has been subsidizing since April, the price of gas would have passed the all-time high of NIS 8.25 per liter.
The discount expires at the end of July and the Tax Authority and the Treasury are currently promoting the publication for public comment of a decree extending the reduction in the tax on gasoline, which is half a shekel per liter, until August 9.
Also, starting on August 10, a further reduction of another half shekel will be established, so that only from this date the price of a liter of gasoline will decrease by one shekel until November 15, 2022.
This was reported by the Tax Authority.
"We have reached a situation where I do not remember five months in a row of a surplus in state revenues.
We started a few months ago with the issue of tax cuts on diesel.
We have been working for a week on a four-month extension of the excise, gasoline and diesel tax - instead of half a shekel per shekel.
It's good for the industry and the citizenry.
If we lower, it will affect inflation, lower production and ease the cost of living.
As finance minister, despite the election campaign, I intend to focus first and foremost on this, "Lieberman said at the Horwitz Conference on Economics and Society of the Israel Democracy Institute.
To date, more than half of the price of fuel is the taxes collected by the government (excise tax and VAT) - and this is a high rate of taxation compared to most developed countries.
The price of fuel has a dramatic impact on the cost of living in the economy - because it affects both household and business expenses, the prices of public transportation and flights, transportation costs, and more.
For the third time in a row: Ashdod - the most business-friendly city
Petah Tikva came in second place in the ranking of doing business by the Ministry of Economy
After them: Rehovot, Ashkelon and Rishon LeZion •
Minister Barbibai: "The corona has highlighted the importance of local government in business development"
.
Ashdod is the most friendly city for small and medium-sized businesses.
This is the third year in a row that the Doing Business in Local Authorities Index of the Agency for Small and Medium-Sized Businesses at the Ministry of Economy and Industry has ranked local authorities.
In second place is the city of Petah Tikva and in third place is Rehovot.
They are followed by Ashkelon, Rishon Lezion, Tel Aviv-Jaffa, Haifa, Ramat Gan, Holon, Beer Sheva, Jerusalem, Bat Yam, Netanya and Bnei Brak.
The agency compiles the Local Authorities Index.
This is the fifth time and its purpose is to serve as a working tool for the local authority, as it allows each authority to compare its performance with other authorities in a variety of parameters, as well as to analyze its performance in the areas in which it is active.
The index is based on several parameters that are tested in each authority, which examine the level of "friendliness" of the authority to businesses in its area.
The index divides the authorities into three size groups according to the number of residents, since a local authority of up to 50,000 residents is not comparable to a local authority of more than 150,000 residents.
TA surged this year
The index is updated once a year and weighs four different ratings in each local authority: Business satisfaction, accessibility to tenders, accessibility of information and property taxes.
The ranking shows that Ramat Gan dropped from second to eighth place, Bat Yam dropped from fourth to 12th place and Netanya dropped from fifth to 13th place.
A decrease in the rating does not mean that the authority's service to businesses has deteriorated, and in many cases it is due to the fact that the service of other authorities to businesses has improved more and they have risen in the rating, while the authority that has decreased in the rating has improved its services to businesses less.
Among those rising in the ranking are Petah Tikva, which rose from sixth to second place, and Rehovot, which rose from 12th to third place.
Tel Aviv, which dropped from fourth to 11th place in 2019, improved in 2021 and rose to sixth place.
"Business as an engine of growth"
The ranking shows that Nof Hagalil leads in local authorities with between 50,000 and 150,000 residents.
It is followed by Kiryat Motzkin, Mata Binyamin, Modiin-Maccabim-Reut, Kfar Saba, Ra'anana, Nahariya, Karmiel, Afula and Hod Hasharon.
In the 28th and last place is Tiberias.
"The measure is intended to encourage local authorities to facilitate small and medium-sized businesses, starting from the date of opening the business and throughout its activity with the authorities," says Economy and Industry Minister Orna Barbibai.
"Businesses are a significant growth engine for the Israeli economy and are responsible for about 50% of business output and about 60% of those employed in the economy.
The development of small businesses is in the public interest of all of us, but the local authority has a direct impact on the businesses that are in it.
The coronavirus has highlighted the importance of local government and we have seen that authorities that have acted and encouraged the promotion of small businesses and found creative solutions for them, have become the first governmental interface for them. "
Ran Koiti, director of the Small and Medium Business Agency at the Ministry of Economy and Industry, adds: "Local authorities play a central and essential role in the ability of businesses in their field to thrive and flourish.
In the last two years, when we are dealing with the coronavirus crisis, the authorities have a greater weight in helping businesses survive in their field and survive in general. "
2021 in the mail: 20 packages for every household - and a surge in their weight
46.6 million packages arrived in Israel during 2021 - similar to 2020
The average weight per package is 435 grams - a jump of 36% compared to 2020 •
The busiest month: December, when the average package weight was 524 grams.
In 2021, 46.6 million mail packages arrived in Israel, almost 20 packages on average per household - according to Israel Post data obtained by "Israel Today."
The number of packages that arrived in 2021 is similar to 2020, when 46.5 million packages arrived in Israel, and lower than 2019, when 61.6 million packages arrived.
However, this year there was a jump of more than 36% in the weight of packages arriving from abroad.
In 2021, 20,253 tons of products arrived in Israel from abroad, a jump of 36% compared to 14,860 tons in 2020, and 16,743 tons in 2019.
Changes in consumption habits
The average weight per package jumped by 60% in two years - from 272 grams in 2019 to 435 grams in 2021.
The surge in the weight of packages is mainly influenced by two major trends, both on the part of the seller and the buyer: The largest shopping sites abroad combine items into one shipment and no longer send each product from the "shopping basket" in separate packaging.
On the part of the Israeli consumer, the fast delivery of shipments, within a few days of ordering, supports the purchase of more everyday products such as clothing and gifts, which buyers want to receive near the time of purchase.
Also in 2021, as in 2020 and 2019, the month in which the most packages arrived from abroad with the highest weight and the highest number of items is December, with 4.2 million packages with a total weight of 2,200 tons.
In December, the average weight per package was 524 grams, 20% higher than the annual average weight.
The Black Friday effect
More packages arrived in December than any other month, probably following the November shopping holidays, such as Chinese Singles Day, Black Friday and Cyber Monday.
Large orders begin to arrive in Israel between one and two weeks after the purchase.
Survey: Most Americans Don't Know They Can Get Tax Refunds
Many employees deserve money from the state, which can reach tens of thousands of shekels.
Have you changed place of work?
Did you go out to the ICU?
Have you moved out of town?
You may be entitled to receive a substantial amount in a simple procedure •
All the details - inside.
Most employees are not aware of the fact that they are entitled to tax refunds, which can accumulate to high amounts.
The State Comptroller noted in a report from about two months ago that two million employees are entitled to tax refunds of NIS 3.6 billion, which means that you should also check whether you are eligible to receive tax refunds.
Many hires can receive a high amount, as four out of five hires are eligible for tax refunds.
In practice, however, they serve several tens of thousands of hires a year.
If you think that these funds went to waste anyway, think again: Employees can apply to the IRS for refunds for six years back.
Tax: On conducted an in-depth study among 4,000 of its clients regarding tax returns during 2020.
The company has more than 30,000 customers, so the sample reflects their dispersion in terms of population groups and in terms of gender, age and geography.
The data shows that during 2020, due to the outbreak of the corona crisis and the expenditure of hundreds of thousands of employees on HALAT, there were a number of significant changes, mainly a 15% increase in the average return to a household, which amounted to NIS 4,300 per year.
The reason is that the salary is lower than the salary and therefore there is a gap between what the employee paid as tax and what he actually needs.
By the way, the highest refund received in 2020 by a client of the company was NIS 121,054 for refunds over the past 6 years.
What can I get a tax refund for?
One of the reasons to get tax refunds is a change in workplace.
81% of the people who changed jobs during the year received an average tax refund of NIS 2,943.
Another reason is maternity leave.
The data shows that 74% of women who gave birth and were on maternity leave for more than 16 weeks were entitled to a refund of an average of NIS 3,538 for that year.
Another reason for the refund is donations.
100% of people who donate and pay taxes have been reimbursed.
Another factor for reimbursement is not registering credits for alimony. 63%
The divorced did not update a credit point for alimony, so the tax refund for each year that such a credit point was not updated is NIS 2,616.
Due to Unemployment - Expenditure on Social Security: 93% of those who became sick or unemployed and earned over NIS 12,000 received a tax refund of NIS 4,021 for the same year.
Other reasons for tax refunds are: Reimbursement for life insurance payments, life insurance on a mortgage, reimbursement for qualifying return, reimbursement for losses in securities, failure to register credit points for a man for giving birth, and distribution of tax refunds by geographic location.
- 94% of people who deposited for personal life insurance or for taking out a mortgage were eligible for a tax refund.
In an examination conducted on each million shekels of a 25-year mortgage, the cumulative tax refund for the period is over 20,000 shekels for the entire mortgage period
100% of those who move to a qualifying settlement received a tax refund for the transition year, since confirmation of residency in a qualifying settlement is given only after 12 months from the date the resident becomes a qualifying resident, and thus in fact the first year full tax is paid.
79% of the customers holding securities were entitled to the tax refund of the said years.
However, it is important for those who hold securities to check every year since losses are not rolled over from year to year but only through the filing of a report.
56% of men who had a child do not record credit points in the year of birth on the pay slip.
The repayment rate can reach tens of thousands of shekels over 6 years.
This is a phenomenon that exists mainly in the Arab sector.
CEO of tax: On, Tal Carmon: "The coronavirus crisis has caused the salaried public in Israel to become much more active.
He takes an interest, checks and demands what he deserves in refunds from the IRS.
It turns out that the fact that hundreds of thousands of Israelis have been sitting at home, in HALAT or after layoffs, for months on end, has caused many employees to take a deep look at what they deserve from the state.
It is important to know that today it is possible to carry out all the procedures for obtaining tax returns digitally, easily and simply, without the bureaucracy that deterred many in the past. "
Job market: Fewer job applicants, more pay
AllJobs Report for 2021: At the top of demand - jobs without experience •
The volume of jobs offered increased by 50% •
"Looking for a job, but not storming the market"
In the year that just ended, there was a 15% decrease in the number of resumes sent, and an average of only 23 candidates competed for each position, compared to 41 candidates in the previous year - according to a report by the Olajobs website summarizing the year 2021, on the coronavirus crisis and its effects on the labor market in Israel.
According to the report, job seekers were mainly interested in job-rich areas such as administration and sales, for which 1,738,485 resumes were sent.
However, jobs without experience led the demand with more than 38 thousand searches - probably due to the return of young people without professional experience to look for immediate work, at the end of the salary payments.
The number of searches for sales and administration was 35,000 and 32,000 (respectively), drivers and couriers had 11,000 searches, and maintenance had just under 9,000 searches.
On the other hand, despite the coronavirus crisis, wages in 2021 increased by 2% compared to 2020, and the average wage in Israel stood at NIS 11,675 gross.
The average monthly salary in the software field was NIS 17,915, and in information systems analysis it was NIS 17,140.
However, between the center and the periphery there was a wage gap of more than NIS 2,000: In the center of the country it was NIS 12,500 on average, compared to NIS 10,795 in the north and NIS 10,135 in the south.
From a gender perspective, the average wage gap between women and men, which can also be explained by the type of work and the number of hours worked, remained at 36%.
Men earned NIS 13,295, while women earned NIS 9,740.
Trying to get back in the furrow
On the business side, there was lateral growth in almost all sectors of the economy, and businesses longed for working hands.
Thus, the supply of jobs increased by 50% and recorded a record of more than 40 thousand jobs in Alljobs.
A survey conducted by the site among employers found that 50% were optimistic about their financial status in 2022, 30% of them indicated their intention to increase total recruitments but 72% understand that they will have difficulty doing so this year.
The largest supply was for jobs without experience - and there were more than 58 thousand of them on the site.
They were followed by customer service and administration positions with about 44,000 jobs in each area, sales and software with 41,000 jobs each, teaching and education with 24,000 vacancies, and warehouses still in demand with 19,000 vacancies.
Einav Boimfeld, director of research and content at Oljobs: "Job seekers are trying to get back on track but are not storming the market, mainly due to the lack of attractive jobs in their eyes.
Also, the prolonged disconnection from the work cycle makes it difficult for them to return, and some have found creative ways to earn a living. "
Israel's unemployment rate rises to 6.3%
The Bureau's survey data shows that about 270 thousand Israelis remained unemployed in December 2021 •
In November, there were 262,000 unemployed.
The percentage of unemployed in the first half of December 2021 was 6.3%, about 270 thousand Israelis, compared to 6.1% in the second half of November 2021 (about 262 thousand).
This is according to data from a workforce survey for the first half of the month of December 2021 by the Central Bureau of Statistics.
The percentage of the unemployed stood at 4.5% in the first half of December 2021 compared to 4.3% in the second half of November 2021.
In other words, it is 193 thousand unemployed compared to 180.3 thousand.
According to the characteristics of the labor force in the first half of December 2021 among those aged 15 and over, it appears that this population included 6,607,500 residents in Israel, not including institutions and those living outside the settlements.
Of these, 64.4%, i.e. 4,252,700 are in the labor force and the rest accounting for 2,354,800 are not in the labor force.
Of those in the workforce 95.5% accounting for 4,059,700 are employed and the rest are unemployed.
Of those who are not in the workforce, 2.3% stopped working due to layoffs or job closures from March 2020.
The Labor Force Survey provides information on the labor force in Israel and is conducted on an ongoing basis by the Central Bureau of Statistics.
In the first half of the month of December 2021, approximately 8,700 people aged 15 and over were interviewed on an ongoing basis.
In the second half of the month of November 2021, approximately 8,900 people aged 15 and over were interviewed on an ongoing basis.
The survey population includes permanent residents of the State of Israel, tourists and temporary residents who stay in Israel for more than a year in a row.
The survey allows tracking the development of the labor force, its size and characteristics, the extent of unemployment, and more.
"Not taken for granted": Subliminal sanctifies the Sabbath - and prepares for independence
