When we return home with the gifts, the smells of cooking greet us. "
What does your Friday dinner look like?
"I was blessed with the cooks around me.
On my side there is Persian-Tunisian cuisine, full of salads and an atmosphere of laughter, music, poetry and joy.
From the side of my wife Ines, who is also a great cook, come the Ukrainian dishes, which are deep and spicy, with a lot of meat.
When we get to my mother-in-law, already from the lobby of the building, amazing smells come up from her apartment.
I usually do the Kiddush, together with the children, who know it by heart.
In the end, my fun after eating is to pass out on the carpet, and the kids jump on me like I'm some inflatable. "
Do you have a special childhood memory from the weekends?
"As a child, I would wake up on Shabbat to the sound of Israeli music on Network C and to the skits of the Pale Tracker, which we knew by heart.
My father loved nature and we traveled a lot in the Land of Israel, usually to the north.
Every corner of the country made him proud.
He died three months ago from a serious illness, and for him Kiddush and Shabbat were holy of holies, mainly in the sense that the whole family should be together.
I recently released a song in his memory called'Keeping You Safe, 'which I created with Usher Cohen.
I believe he would have been proud of this work, which sanctifies the bond between father and son. "
Soon we will celebrate the 74th Independence Day. As an ardent Zionist, what are your feelings about the holiday?
"Independence Day is a sacred day for me, and part of my meaning and identity.
In Persia and Tunisia, my parents had to hide their Jewish identity, while I am an Israeli Jew who is privileged to live with his children in our country.
A week or two before Independence Day, I would climb trees and tie wires with Israeli flags to the house.
Today, my days of independence are full of concerts, and I always meet an insanely happy audience, which celebrates the fact that we can live the way we want.
We must ensure that our children, grandchildren and great-grandchildren also have this opportunity, and remember that nothing here is taken for granted. "
Her Friday: Estee Zakheim Welcomes the Sabbath
"My dream is to open a big table and invite all my dead loved ones": A Friday dinner that Esti Zakheim dreams of, and how does she cope with the fact that her husband keeps Shabbat?
Tell us about your preparations for Saturday.
.
"The preparations start as early as Thursday night, when I return from a show or a workshop and cook until three in the morning everything that requires long cooking such as goulash, roasts and sauces.
