At Shabbat dinner, I usually host my mother, Varda, who celebrated her 89th birthday, and also friends. "
Can you share more cooking?
"I like the short cuts.
For instance, instead of peeling 10 onions, slicing and dicing, I buy a bag of frozen onions and fry it.
On my Shabbat table you can find meat dishes, vegan tofu dishes, potatoes and cauliflower in the oven.
I do most of the cooking, and of course they heat up on the platter on Saturday.
Alejandro, my partner, makes chicken soup, vegetable salad and in the winter - the cholent. "
Your husband is a religious man and you are from a secular home.
How does it work?
"Living with a Shabbat keeper is an endless compromise.
"And you shall love your neighbor as yourself," in effect.
For family trips, he can't go out, so I found myself many times packing up the kids and joining friends' family trips.
In addition, I am also the children's driver on duty, the one who brings them back on Friday night from parties and gatherings.
On the other hand, I also enjoy the benefits of his Shabbat, because I usually don't show up on Shabbat and get a kind of'forced vacation '- and that's good. "
Who would you like to host on Saturday?
"I would open a big table and invite my dead.
