The low volume of tests makes it difficult to identify and understand morbidity trends. "
The State Comptroller's Report: The Actual Budget in Most Years of the Drug Basket Committee's Activity - Less Than the Recommended Budget
According to Netanyahu Engelman's report, for more than 20 years of the basket's activity - the Ministry of Health did not supervise the committee's activities •
The report also states that the minutes of the sittings are published significantly late, if at all •
In addition, the auditor recommends increasing the transparency of the subcommittee's activities - and updating the basket work procedures •
Another defect that was found concerns the fact that since the committee began its activities, the Ministry of Health has not asked the health funds for reports on the extent of use and utilization of the drugs in the basket - which would have made it possible to analyze and audit the budget given to them.
The Medicines Basket Committee is one of the most influential public committees on our daily lives and our health.
Every year, the committee decides on new drugs that will be given to the public free of charge through the health funds - but a new report by the State Comptroller published on Tuesday warns that it has been operating for more than 20 years without control reports on its activities and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Council supervising and examining its activities.
"Israel Hayom" correspondent Ran Resnik adds that the State Comptroller's investigation was conducted following the ongoing disclosures in "Israel Hayom" about the omissions in the drug basket.
According to Netanyahu Engelman's report, he recommends "making corrections and improvements in the process of expanding the basket, which will lead to a better utilization of the health care basket budget that the public is entitled to."
Throughout the years of the existence of the addition mechanism to the basket of medicines, in the years 1998-2021, medicines totaling eight billion shekels were added to the state budget - with the addition ranging annually in amounts ranging from 0 to 500 million shekels.
In 2019, 2020 and 2021, applications were submitted to add about 800 new drugs and technologies to the health care basket, at a total annual cost of more than NIS 2 billion.
In practice, the budget allocated for expanding the basket was smaller than the volume of requests.
In most of the years of the committee's operation (90% of the time), the amount of the budget supplement was less than 1.5% of the health basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired supplement rate.
The auditor notes that it is necessary to examine and regulate the amount of the annual increment in order to allow certainty and long-term planning.
Engelman also noted that "the transparency model in the basket work is lacking."
Thus, for example, the procedure for the work of the basket committee states that the minutes of the meetings, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days, but in practice the minutes are published with a delay of 160-109 days, when sometimes the minutes of the final meetings are not published at all.
"The delay in the publication of the protocols harms the transparency of the decisions; as a result, the ability of the proposers - patient organizations and pharmaceutical companies - to submit repeated applications as soon as possible and relevant, after they have learned from the rejection of their proposals, analyzed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and amended their proposals and reassessed their feasibility for acceptance in the next round, may be impaired," the auditor noted in the report.
"The Ministry of Health must publish the protocols in accordance with the schedules established in the procedure."
Out of thousands of submissions - only one financial note was submitted
Another criticism by Engelman concerns the preliminary procedure of evaluating the technologies submitted to the drug basket.
The auditor found that about half (46%) of the submitted technologies did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for the rejection.
Another deficiency concerns the activities of the drug basket subcommittee, which is closed to the media and the public, and where patient numbers and drug costs are discussed.
The auditor recommends that a public representative be attached or that the possibility be explored of publishing the discussions to the public without confidential commercial details.
The procedure according to which the Health Services Basket Committee operates states that "an economic assessment must be submitted" for an application to add a medicine to the basket.
But in practice, over the years, only one economic assessment has been submitted out of thousands of submissions - and the committee makes its decisions without an economic assessment.
For example, for the 2021-2019 basket committee hearings, applications were submitted to add anti-obesity drugs to the basket.
The report showed that the requests were not accompanied by economic estimates, including an estimate of the amount that could have been saved due to reducing the damage of diseases caused by obesity or due to the ability to avoid gastric surgery.
It also shows that the decisions of the Medicines Basket Committee are inconsistent with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
For example, in 2019, the Ministry of Health defined preventive medicine and preparation for the treatment of an increase in chronic diseases as goals, but in the framework of the decisions regarding the expansion of the basket, no emphasis was placed on the need to achieve these goals.
The Comptroller also warns that since 2011, services that are not the responsibility of the HMOs, including rehabilitation and mobility devices and various vaccines, provided by the Ministry of Health (the "Third Supplement"), have also been included in the basket of medicines.
This is when the legal framework for this step is regulated only retrospectively.
In the last six years, NIS 74 million of the addition to the drug basket has been used for these services.
Engelman recommends that the Ministry of Health update the basket work procedures and also determine whether a separate financial supplement is needed for these services.
About a third of the new drugs that enter the drug basket are defined as "drugs without additional cost," the use of which does not cost the health funds an additional amount because they replace existing treatment.
The auditor suggests examining the possibility that these drugs will be discussed in a different and shortened route, so that the basket of drugs can be updated several times a year and not just once a year.
There is no oversight of the use of extremely expensive drugs.
The audit also shows that since the work of the basket committee began 20 years ago, the Ministry of Health has not asked the health funds to report and has not monitored the extent of the use and utilization of the drugs in the basket, information that could have allowed the ministry to analyze and audit the budget given to the funds.
Over the years, only two reports have been published that refer to the years 2006-2009, and these were also published with considerable delay (the last one was published this year and dealt with the utilization of the budget in 2007-2009).
"The delay in conducting tests may lead to difficulty in collecting and analyzing the data, the irrelevance of the conclusions emerging from the test after such a long period of time, the subcommittee's non-optimal pricing and decision-making based on inconclusive findings," the report said.
The ministry also does not audit and monitor the use of extremely expensive drugs and has not learned any lessons.
These are 10 drugs that accounted for 62% of the addition to the basket (NIS 1.7 billion in 2021-2016).
On this, the auditor wrote: "It is recommended that the Ministry of Health carry out individual controls on these drugs and technologies and analyze the extent of their use compared to the estimates.
Controls and analysis will make it possible to draw systemic conclusions about the work process of the basket committee and the sub-committee, and about how to prepare estimates when pricing drugs and technologies and improve them. "
