The compensation also includes medical expenses, the cost of medical and rehabilitation accessories, the cost of adapting housing to the baby's needs, mobility and more.
"The amount of compensation is determined on a case-by-case basis and according to the circumstances," says Attorney Reif-Liganza, and she adds and notes that "today, most claims on the grounds of medical negligence end in a compromise that weighs the chance and risk that each party has in conducting the procedure," but the attorney added and said that "there are cases in which the procedure ends only with a judgment, then if the claim is not rejected, the plaintiffs will receive full compensation for all their damages and, for example, in a lawsuit conducted by our office, the district court awarded a minor who suffered cerebral palsy due to a delay in identifying fetal distress compensation in excess of ten million shekels."
To sum up
Medical malpractice at birth is undoubtedly the nightmare of every family.
In these cases, a proper legal examination of the sequence of events that caused the tragic outcome, by a lawyer skilled in managing claims on the grounds of medical negligence, can help you win the compensation you deserve.
This is the reason for the prevalence of keratoconus eye disease in the South
A study has shown that there is a link between the development of the disease and close marriages •
The highest incidence was found in the Bedouin sector •
Expert: "It is possible that in any sector with a lot of weddings between cousins, we will find a high incidence of the disease."
Keratoconus is a hereditary eye disease that causes some visual impairments.
It is very important to diagnose it as soon as possible, and find the right solutions to prevent the situation from worsening.
In recent years, several studies have been conducted to help understand how the disease develops, and innovative treatments have been developed.
The new studies provide a scientific basis for the suspicion that keratoconus eye disease is a genetic disease.
A recent study, which dealt with the transformation of the shape of the cornea from a dome to a cone, revealed that the cause of the disease and the weakness of the cornea and its deformation is related to an enzyme imbalance, following which the free radicals can damage the proteins in the cornea - and its structure will change.
The source of that enzyme deficiency is genetic, a fact that reinforces the hypothesis that keratoconus is an inherited disease.
According to Prof. Ariela Gordon-Shag, head of the Department of Optometric Sciences at Hadassah Academic College, "In a study published in the field among Arab students in Haifa, a prevalence of keratoconus of 3.2% was found.
The highest incidence was among students from the Bedouin sector - 20% had keratoconus, but there was a small relative sample. "
The researcher added that this is not a surprising finding: "There is a large prevalence of keratoconus in the Bedouin sector.
In our studies, we found that close marriages are a risk factor for keratoconus disease.
So in any sector with a lot of weddings between cousins, we may find a high incidence. "
In this context, it should be noted that this is an important finding in light of the unequivocal conclusion: In cases where a family history of keratoconus disease appears, all family members should access an appropriate eye examination as soon as possible.
According to Arza Fruchter, a B.Sc clinical optometrist, "there is a tenfold appeal to the clinic from remote periphery areas, mainly from the southern region, compared to the center."
"Over the past decade, I have noticed that most patients are turning away from the periphery, especially from the Be'er Sheva area.
This is mainly due to the high incidence of marriages within the family (especially in the Bedouin sector) and various allergies, and a lack of awareness of proper treatment of the problem. "
So how is the disease diagnosed?
Fruchter explains that keratoconus usually develops in adolescence or in the late teens (ages 16-15 or 20).
The disease involves a decrease in vision, coinciding with an increase in the cylinder.
Keratoconus patients have distorted and / or blurred vision of figures and objects.
These signs worsen with the development of the disease, which usually develops slowly and gradually over years.
However, the disease may also develop at a rapid rate and reach its peak in just a few months.
Many patients also show increased sensitivity to light.
