"In order to address this phenomenon, their motivation to go to work in Israel must be sterilized, and the Israeli side must charge them a price that will prevent them from crossing the fence.
Sources involved in the matter claim that the failure to collect the price is due, among other things, to a lack of places of confinement and the fact that the arrests are made only when there are related offenses or it is a recidivist.
Legal sources claim that the decision to charge a fee only starting with his third arrest was made, among other things, because the courts cannot cope with the number of arrests carried out every day.
Anyone who examines the punishment will find that it is not a deterrent. "
There is a great complexity
Sheba, "says a police source," is a complex person. "
He can be a father of a family who entered the country to work to earn a few shekels and return.
This is the basic platform, and on it are dressed many types of prisoners who enter the country to commit criminal offenses or terrorist attacks. "
It can be adult or minor.
In the past, 16-year-old illegal residents have been caught by the police, and even 8- and 10-year-olds are sent by their parents to road junctions to earn a few shekels a day from driving.
"It also makes the matter complicated, because in such cases we have to bring the parents and file an indictment against them for neglect," says a senior police officer.
Most Palestinians are employed in Israel in manual labor.
The most unusual are electrical work or advanced construction work.
In the past, there were also local authorities that employed IPS in garbage disposal, mainly in the north.
Out of 34 crossings, there are about 18 major crossings.
There are crossings of vehicles and goods, there are crossings through which only people pass, and there are crossings that are both.
All crossings are supervised by the IDF and the crossings authority.
The Shin Bet are usually driven into the country by private drivers, as it is easy money.
"There are those who do this for a living and there are gangs whose main occupation is transporting prisoners," says a senior police official, "usually most of them are Israeli Arabs, who speak the same language and correspond with them.
It can go from $100 to $300 per person.
