"Israel Hayom" unveiling: A glimpse of the "Assaf" installation
Popular terrorism focuses on harming civilians and aims to undermine the sense of security necessary to lead a normal life of a civilian population.
The severe wave of attacks that took place this year, with attacks in Be'er Sheva, Hadera, Bnei Brak, Ariel, Elad, and especially the one that took place in early April on the busy Dizengoff Street in the heart of Tel Aviv, by a terrorist who assimilated into the crowd, led the police to think creatively in order to develop a tool that could be used to train fighters to attack terrorists within a civilian population.
The thinking was led by the training division of the police and the border guard.
These came out in a competition in the various police districts under the title "Commanders Lead Learning," in which each district was required to develop measures that would help improve the policing and combat skills of the fighters, police officers and commanders.
As part of the competition, and as a response to the need to train Border Police fighters for combat training in shooting in motion and in such descriptions, Assaf Ben David, a counter-terrorism instructor of the Jerusalem Border Police, developed the "Assaf facility," which consists of a dynamic target, which is connected to a telescopic pole on which a carrier can be harnessed to the instructor.
Their servant who guides the carrier to his death, he can practice the warrior standing in front of him by controlling and moving the target to different sides and ranges.
It should be emphasized that in recent years, Border Guard fighters have faced many attacks in which the assailant, carries out gunfire and poses a threat while on the move in arenas saturated with innocent civilians.
The "Assaf facility," in its current version, is based on components and parts that are used in various fields.
For example, the telescopic pole that was upgraded and integrated into the facility was taken from the maintenance and cleaning area.
Using the facility, it is possible to simulate shooting in motion within a civilian population towards a dynamic target while maintaining eye contact with the object, handling a traffic stop, choosing a path of progress and performing selective shooting, including the practice of preventing injury to the uninvolved.
Major Assaf Ben David, after whom the facility is named, says: "The facility we developed is a breakthrough in the learning and training of soldiers and police officers.
The development provides a relevant response to the threats of attribution and simulates the reality on the ground.
The benefit of development compared to the relatively cheap cost of production gives us a significant competitive advantage. "
