Study states: Zoom meetings hurt creativity
Some 2,100 engineers and academics around the world were asked to develop solutions to the problem - some in video sessions, some in face-to-face meetings •
The result: A virtual meeting hurts creativity and thinking outside the box •
Research leader at Columbia University: "The visual focus on the screen harms the process of creating ideas"
Nehema Porta: There is no harm to productivity or critical thinking.
A large scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature examined the impact of video sessions on the creativity of their participants, compared to face-to-face sessions.
Sadly, it has been found that creativity does get compromised in virtual meetings through screens.
The research question - led by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia University - was whether remote meetings using a computer preserve the creativity that exists in office brainstorming sessions, or whether the level of creativity and free thinking decreases as a result of remoteness.
The research itself began as early as 2016 but got a big boost during the two years of the coronavirus, during which many employees switched to working from home.
"People in an in-person meeting move around the room, use objects and use them for creative thinking," says Brooks.
"In a computer meeting, on the other hand, the concentration on maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative activity in the brain.
The visual focus on the screen reduces cognition.
People are more focused on video when interacting, which impairs the broad and expansive idea creation process. "
The space is shrinking.
To test the results of the experiment and make sure they would be repeated, they were tested twice - once at Columbia University and once more in real life - on engineers who knew each other from early acquaintance.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 faculty members and students into two parts - in one, the subjects were asked to meet in person and develop solutions to the problem, and in the other, they were asked to do so through a computer.
At the same time, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia were asked to divide themselves in a similar way and solve a problem presented to them in a new way.
In both cases, a decrease in creativity and out-of-the-box thinking was found among those who met virtually on video.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher who studies ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
In his opinion, as part of a thinking activity, people often look at their surroundings to help create ideas, while in a video session, thinking converges on the screen and does not expand in a way that allows creativity.
"When people are in the same room, they look around and see the space, where there are objects and situations that can evoke new associations.
On the other hand, the study shows that relationships through a computer change our attention so that we are more focused inward and on the screen, and this way reduces innovation and the creation of ideas through looking at the environment and thinking outside. "
There is no harm in critical thinking.
However, before managers rush employees back to the offices, the researchers note that "working through a computer did not harm productivity itself nor people's critical thinking about innovative proposals, when they had to choose the best idea from a set of ideas.
In other words, the harm is aimed only at creativity and not at other forms of work in front of a computer. "
Professor Ellen Langer, a professor of psychology at Harvard University, also disapproves of the findings.
According to her, "There is a difference between just creativity, such as new uses for Frisbee (one of the research questions) and solutions of work.
It's also possible that when employees are more relaxed after getting to know each other, or when they work from home, creativity will improve. "
Both Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson also proposed a future study in which such meetings would be interrupted for thinking situations and wandering around the room to see how this activity would affect the final result.
Dr. Olson also suggested that following the study, only for brainstorming sessions would employees return to work and as a general rule, he suggested not to be alarmed by one study but to conduct another investigation in the field.
"I wouldn't want workers to be forced back and not being happy is a bigger hurt" he says.
