We checked: What do the side effects after the coronavirus vaccine say?
Many people who get vaccinated feel weakness, fever and fatigue after getting the shot, while others feel nothing •
Could this indicate a stronger immune system in those who do experience these symptoms, or is it a baseless rumor?
As more and more people get vaccinated, the lack of information about the side effects continues to confuse and create rumors, most of which are untrue.
Is the immune system of those who developed side effects stronger than those whose bodies responded less severely to the vaccine, which could perhaps prove that their system is unable to fight off a foreign body entering the body?
"There are several levels of reactions to the vaccine," says Dr. David Dvir, head of the division of primary medicine at the United Nations and a member of the advisory committee for the TCM (Pandemic Treatment Team), and reassures: "Headaches, fatigue, pain in place, these are the immediate reactions of the immune system.
This is how the body reacts when a foreign body enters the system. "
Is there a link between the levels of antibodies one develops and the side effects?
"There is no correlation between the sensations and the development of antibodies against the virus.
About 60% -50% experience side effects, but about 90% develop protection against the virus.
People who developed stronger responses were not found to be more protected. "
"In the medical literature, there is no correlation between an immediate response and the level of vaccination.
In some trials where people also received placebo vaccines, about a quarter of them developed headaches.
This is also a mental component - how the person perceives the vaccine, if they expect there to be side effects.
Many of the phenomena that happen could also happen normally, but since the public has been vaccinated, it attributes the reaction to the vaccine itself, and this is the bias that we see regarding vaccines in general - attribution of phenomena that happen near the vaccine and are attributed to it. "
According to Dr. Dvir, the reasons for the commonly reported symptoms, such as weakness and headaches, are not yet known.
Regarding myocarditis, opinions are divided.
"There are all kinds of theories about this, but it should be noted that the virus itself causes higher rates of myocarditis than the vaccine.
One theory is that it's a strong immune response. "
Is it even possible to assess the strength of an immune system?
"When students were exposed to the flu virus, it was shown that those who did not sleep or were under higher pressure were more vulnerable to infection.
Apart from this, there are laboratory parameters that test the immune system or its components.
When there is a decline in the immune system, you see it immediately.
People are contracting a lot of viral or infectious diseases.
It's not that someone is walking around with a weak immune system and not aware of it.
These are people who come for inquiries because of repeated incidents of infectious diseases, and what affects the system are banal things: Stress, nutrition, sleep.
By the way, we also don't want an immune system that is too strong, because it can cause autoimmune diseases. "
Soon, mRNA vaccines will appear in additional contexts, thanks to the extensive knowledge that has accumulated about them in recent times.
"There is no doubt that it will pave the way for other vaccines of this kind.
This technology is being tested for many uses beyond vaccines - for the treatment of oncological diseases, for example.
Their effectiveness is that the substance remains very little time in the body - enters, does its action, and then breaks down.
This technology is not new, but it has received a serious boost following the very great need for a quick vaccine.
Now, for example, we know that a three-week interval between doses is too small, and some vaccine experts claim that after a third dose we may not need another vaccine in the near term, so it is not clear whether we are going to a situation of vaccination every six months or the third dose will give a larger interval. "
Thousands injured: Serious privacy omission on Highway 6
Customers of Route 6?
Your personal information, including full name, addresses, payment amounts and full details of the trips you have taken, may have been disclosed.
According to the Privacy Protection Authority, Derech Eretz violated the Privacy Protection Law and its regulations.
Following a report submitted by Derech Eretz, the operator of Route 6 in Israel, about a security incident that occurred at the company, the Privacy Protection Authority began an enforcement procedure.
As part of the incident, security weaknesses were discovered on its payment site, which allowed the disclosure of a lot of information from the invoices of the member's customers, which were exposed to all eyes.
Among other things, customers' payment invoices were exposed over a long period of time and these invoices included personal information, including first and last name, payment amounts, location of the vehicle, travel dates and at what times.
In addition, since Derech Eretz did not document access to its systems as required by law, it is not possible to know precisely for how long unauthorized parties could access the company's systems.
In the violation letter, which the Privacy Protection Authority sent to the company, the Authority emphasized that most companies and large organizations in the economy are required to adopt a dynamic information security policy, and that with the development of threats and risks, the organization has an obligation to rigorously examine the updated risks and act in accordance with the update of the security measures accepted in the circumstances, in accordance with the nature and nature of the database.
As a result, companies and organizations are required to update their systems and conduct risk surveys and penetration tests to examine and prepare for the changing risks.
In addition, companies and organizations are required to use an automatic documentation mechanism and training must be conducted for employees, in accordance with the provisions of the Privacy Protection (Information Security) Regulations.
In accordance with the findings of the inspection, the Authority determined that the company violated the provisions of the Privacy Protection Law and its regulations, and also required the company to take a number of corrective actions.
Derech Eretz, the operator of Route 6, said: "The issue was handled in accordance with the strictest requirements."
