In addition: Tourists from orange destinations will be able to enter the country and the removal of many red destinations from the list is expected.
At the height of a pandemic - the end to isolation for returnees from abroad?
The Ministry of Health sent notices to returnees to Israel on Monday morning, according to which they are exempt from isolation upon receiving a negative answer to the coronavirus test they took after landing in Israel.
It's also about returning from red states.
Some of the messages sent informed the returnees that they could be released after receiving a negative reply or after 24 hours at the latest, and some of them received the exemption after receiving the negative reply.
Only after that did an official announcement come out from the Ministry of Health stating that starting tonight at midnight, January 4, 2022, vaccinated or recovered, returnees from orange countries will take a PCR test at Ben Gurion Airport and go into isolation for 24 hours or until a negative result is received (whichever comes first).
The decision will be enshrined in the order of the Director General of the Ministry of Health and will be submitted to the Knesset Health Committee for approval.
The ministry clarified that vaccinated or recovered people who have already returned to Israel from an orange country and received a negative result from the PCR test they took upon entering Israel will end isolation tonight at midnight and are not obliged to take a second test.
Despite this, passengers from red countries reported that they too had received the message.
Those who have not been vaccinated or recovered and returned from an orange country will enter home isolation for 14 days, with the possibility of shortening isolation upon receiving a negative result in a PCR test performed starting from the 7th day of landing in Israel (the day of landing is the first day).
The decision to remove most of the restrictions on flights and especially on the vaccinated comes a day before the hearing in the High Court of Justice submitted by the Association of Travel Agencies, the Headquarters for Open Skies and the Hotel Association.
At a hearing to be held tomorrow, the petitioners are expected to demand that all other red states be removed from the list, with Professor Itamar Grotto backing them in his opinion.
Foreigners will also be able to enter.
The Prime Minister and the Ministers of Foreign Affairs, Health, Interior, Tourism and Transport agreed that as of Sunday, January 9, 2022, vaccinated / recovered foreigners (as defined by the Ministry of Health) from orange countries will be allowed to enter - subject to filling out an online form in advance, taking a PCR or antigen test before boarding, taking a PCR test upon entering Israel and then entering isolation for 24 hours or receiving a negative test result (whichever comes first).
Unvaccinated / non-recovered foreigners (as defined by the Ministry of Health) will not be allowed to enter Israel.
Foreigners from red countries, except those whose entry has been approved by the exceptions committee, will not be allowed to enter Israel.
The group layout will not be renewed at this time.
And what about red states?
The Committee for the Classification of Countries at the Ministry of Health recommends that the government remove from the list of red countries and transfer to the orange list the countries: South Africa, Hungary, Nigeria, Spain, Portugal, France, Canada.
The countries that remain on the red list at this stage are: The United Arab Emirates, the United States, Ethiopia, the United Kingdom, Tanzania, Mexico, Switzerland and Turkey.
Another option that the Ministry of Health is considering is to exempt from isolation the vaccinated who return from red countries.
