The Ministry of Health decided to recommend canceling the obligation to isolate for three days for Israelis returning from orange countries.
Until now, anyone vaccinated or recovered according to the definitions of the Ministry of Health who returned from an orange country - was required to isolate for three days, subject to two corona tests.
Now, the isolation that the vaccinated and recovered returning from orange countries will have to enter is for a maximum of 24 hours, or until the results of the coronavirus tests are received after landing at Ben Gurion Airport (whichever comes first).
Those who are not defined as vaccinated or recovered will nevertheless be required to enter seven days of isolation subject to two corona tests, or 14 days without the second test, both if returning from an orange country and if returning from a red country.
Vaccinated or recovered who returned from a red country must also be in full isolation.
The latest list of red countries recommended by the Ministry of Health, which still needs to pass government approval, includes the US, Turkey, Tanzania, Ethiopia, Mexico, the UK, Switzerland and the United Arab Emirates.
In all countries, with the exception of Turkey, the average of positives who entered the country in the last two weeks is more than 5% of the total number of arrivals, which automatically puts them on the list of red countries.
The rate of increase in patients from Turkey is rapid, the rate of positive returnees from it is just over 4%, so it was decided to put it on the list of red countries as well.
The notable countries to be removed from the list of red countries: France, Spain, Portugal and Canada.
Meanwhile, starting January 9, tourists who are vaccinated according to the requirements of the Ministry of Health will be able to enter Israel without the need for isolation, similar to the conditions for Israelis returning from an orange country.
Even in this case, the decision is subject to the approval of the government, which will discuss the issue in the coming days.
